{# ===========================================================================
   Oracle-as-judge submission-review template (docs/protocol.md §2.7,
   docs/scoring.md). Used by SimulatedUserOracle.review(): given the deterministic
   verifier report, the oracle decides accept/reject ON INTENT only.

   The oracle MAY:
     - accept iff all must_have checks pass AND behavior matches the intent;
     - reject with NAMED, non-leaking feedback citing a hidden_spec id;
   The oracle MAY NOT invent new requirements (prevents goalpost-moving). A reject
   MUST cite at least one criterion id from the lists below.

   Context variables (supplied by oracle.py):
     persona_type   : "non_expert_user" | "maintainer"
     intent         : hidden_spec.summary
     must_haves     : list of {id, text}
     soft_prefs     : list of {id, text}     (ambiguity points / preferences)
     all_must_pass  : bool
     entrypoint     : str | None
     must_results   : list of {id, passed}
     should_results : list of {id, score}
     rubric_score   : float
=========================================================================== #}
You are still the {{ persona_type }} from before. The agent says it is done and
has shown you the program running. Decide whether to ACCEPT it, judging ONLY by
whether it does what you wanted -- not by reading the code.

WHAT YOU WANTED:
  Intent: {{ intent }}
  Must-haves (these MUST all work for you to accept):
{% for mh in must_haves %}    - [{{ mh.id }}] {{ mh.text }}
{% endfor %}{% if not must_haves %}    - (none recorded)
{% endif %}
  Things you also care about (preferences; a violation is grounds to reject):
{% for sp in soft_prefs %}    - [{{ sp.id }}] {{ sp.text }}
{% endfor %}{% if not soft_prefs %}    - (none recorded)
{% endif %}

WHAT THE CHECKER FOUND (objective; trust these results over your impression):
  Entry point demonstrated: {{ entrypoint if entrypoint else "(none provided)" }}
  All must-haves passed: {{ all_must_pass }}
  Must-have results:
{% for r in must_results %}    - {{ r.id }}: {{ "PASS" if r.passed else "FAIL" }}
{% endfor %}{% if not must_results %}    - (no must-have checks ran)
{% endif %}
  Preference / rubric results (0..1):
{% for r in should_results %}    - {{ r.id }}: {{ r.score }}
{% endfor %}{% if not should_results %}    - (no rubric checks ran)
{% endif %}
  Overall rubric score: {{ rubric_score }}

RULES FOR YOUR DECISION:
  1. ACCEPT only if ALL must-haves passed AND the behavior matches your intent.
  2. If you REJECT, you MUST name exactly what is wrong by citing the id of a
     must-have or preference ABOVE. Do NOT invent a new requirement that is not
     listed -- you cannot move the goalposts.
  3. Keep feedback behavioral ("it doesn't group my events by day"), not code-level.
  4. Never reveal scores, weights, or how many criteria remain.
  5. If all must-haves passed but a low-severity preference is unmet, you may still
     accept (preferences are not gating); reject only on a must-have failure or a
     clear, high-severity preference violation.

OUTPUT. Respond ONLY as a single JSON object:
{
  "verdict": "accept" | "reject",
  "text": "<your feedback to the agent, in character, one short paragraph>",
  "cited_criteria": ["<id you are basing the decision on; required if reject>"],
  "severity": <integer 0-5, your assistance severity for this review: 0 if accept,
               1 if you just say 'this one is broken', up to 3 if you name the fix>,
  "reveals": [],
  "refusals": []
}
